   <BR><img src=http://www.telusplanet.net/public/rmulzet/eq/bearform.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Geforce image quality -- How I improved mine.</span><hr size=1> Well I got this new Geforce2 card and I must say I was not really impressed with the image quality.  Unless standing really close to something/someone, the edges of the image was very jagged.  At a distance most people/armor/faces/buildings became a pixelized mess.  With the improved textures and detail on everyone's armor... it looked pretty bad.<br>
<br>
The thing that made me upset/curious - was that my Voodoo2 was a LOT better quality image, so I figured something must be wrong. As long as 'mip-mapping' was on, my voodoo2 eliminated the jagged edges around the 3D images in the game and genearlly made things look a lot better. Mip-mapping on or off seemed to make no difference with both my old Riva TNT card and my new Geforce2.<br>
<br>
So I took my problem to my cousin that works at Bioware.  He has been working on the 3D engine for Neverwinter Nights for 2 years so I figured he should know something about this. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  I was right, he was bang on.<br>
<br>
Here's how to fix it:<br>
There is an Anti-Aliasing setting in the advanced options of your Geforce card.  Mine was set to &quot;Let the application decide how to use anti-aliasing&quot; which apparently translates into &quot;EQ no use this function, welcome to crappy image&quot;.  <br>
<br>
There are 4 options; 1) leave as is, 2) force anti-aliasing off, 3) force it on 2x, 4) force it on 4x.<br>
<br>
I am not sure what the difference of 2x and 4x mean, possibly the buffer size used to smooth out the image - dunno. The bottom line is that 2x is the minimun setting of 'on' and 4x should be an even better image but possibly lower framerate.  I set mine to 2x and was really blown away by the over all image improvement.  I didn't notice any framerate drop so I am going to try 4x just for kicks.  You might want to try the same if you notice that your Geforce (or other) image is not top-notch.<br>
<br>
Good luck. <p><p align="center"> <img src="http://www.telusplanet.net/public/rmulzet/eq/newsig.jpg"><br> </p>
